ns are discerned.Key FeaturesPresents a comparative approach to miracles in Islam and ChristianityUses the non-judgmental lens of an anthropological and phenomenological approachOrganised around five groups of miracles: food, water, blood, wood and stone, and cosmologyCase studies include miraculous feeding miracles in Islam and Christianity; Lourdes and healing; Zamzam and healing; the miracle of Bolsena; the Passion of Al-Hallaj; the Ark of Gilgamesh and Noah/Nuh; the miracle of the sun at Fatima; and the splitting of the moon in the Qur’an  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aMysticismxChristianity. 0aMysticismxIslam. 4aIslamic Studies. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311078043740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780748699070?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748699070423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748699070/original  a978-3-11-078043-7  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK